{"text": "I'll put this bluntly..this is one of my favorite games of all time.  I stumbled on this game circa 2003 in a bargain bin for a couple of bucks.  Game came in a CD jewel case.  I was just getting into gaming at the time, and had enjoyed the Commandos series, so this enticed me to buy it at the time based on the similar description. Commandos was great, no doubt,  but Desperados 1 took it to a new level for me.  It's combination of real-time squad-based tactics, western-themed story, and just overall charm had me hooked instantly.     It's probably hard to really desrcribe this game for newer gamers these days, since the genre was essentially abandoned many years ago.  However, the new and successful \"Shadow Tactics\" game is directly inspired by this game, so there is a bit of a resurgence for this genre.  In fact, that very same developer just announced Desperados 3, which I'm extremely excited about. Ha..I still own that old cd, plus the GOG version.  Just bought the Steam version mainly to review here, but also as THQ just provided an update to the game for modern systems. D1 has been almost unplayable for quite a few years on newer OS's, so I think it is a testament to the game itself that the publisher would take the time to update the game.   D1 is definitely what I would call a cult classic.  It was never very popular back early 2000s when released, and not even the reviews (professional) were all that glowing.  The squad-based genre in general had always been a bit cultish anyway.  But the thing is that those reviews were simply wrong...not surprisingly.    Many of the reviews I read back at the time simply complained that the game was \"too hard\" or \"trial and error\".   It's hard to take a reviewer seriously when they are used to reviewing RPGs or FPSs.  Desperado/Commando games are very very different than most games. So, the folks that did play the game - all over the world - loved it.  They loved the challenge, the charm, and the trial and error, because the game was designed that way.  Commandos-style is specifically designed not only to be challenging but to use trial and error to solve the tactical challenge.   The game levels are basically like puzzles.  So it is importantant to note that the player can and should save often.  In fact, one can save the game to the immediate point they close the game and reload....so retrying and improving on your tactic is very easy. While in a few situations there is truly a \"best way\" of handling problem,  there are mutiple ways of handling each level or parts of a level.  That is, your use of a particular character's skils or a combination of the teams' skills to solve a problem and clear the path.  So really there's quite some replayiblity in D1.  I've played the game through several times over the years. All six of the characters can be used by the player, though you progressively obtain the characters usually by rescuing them in a higher level. Each character has unique abilities, but all characters possess the ability to shoot a gun or rifle type weapon.  For instance, our hero and main character Matt fires a fast six shooter. His special abilities include a quickdraw in which you can kill at least 3 enemies at once. Also, he can lure enemies with a chiming watch - this comes in useful. Each character has at least 6 unique abilities including a shooting ability. Sam, the second character who is obtained when Matt rescues him in level 2, can use explosives like dynamite, fire a rifle, and use a rattlesnake ( on some levels and with luck the snake can kill off dozens of enemies at once if setup correctly. Doc, the 3rd character, uses a six shooter that doubles as a sniper weapon, plus he can heal. The sexy female Kate is surprsingly valuable with her sex kitten lure and kick ability. I'll stop here with character descriptions, but that gives you a taste. All the character's abilities can be used in creative ways to get through very progressively tough levels.  You'll find that you will get more creative as the game goes along. Another nice feature in the game is that you can record actions for one or multiple characters including running away (very valuable at times). Overall, the game is very hard. It can take a quite a bit of time, strategy, a bit of luck and trial/error to complete all 26 levels. However, I should note that with each new character the developer includes a training level that familiarizes you with their abilities.I have to estimate that I played the game at least 60 hours through for several weeks before completing all levels.  So I do highly recommend this game.  Yes, it is quite an old game now, but the 2D isometric graphics were so wonderfully rendered that the graphics still hold up quite well today, in a harming way.   Play it to get familiar with the genre, or if you are coming over here from just having played \"Shadow Tactics\" ..well..then this game is a must for you as that game is totally dedicated to this one.  Then get ready for the release of Desperados III next year and hopefully a real comeback for this genre.", "appid": "260730", "steamid": "profiles/76561197992286692", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1535198400.0}
