{"text": "QUICK SUMMARY 1) Sekiro is an example of a masterpiece in art form of video games, and this will not be the focus of my review. 2) Some type of gamers will find Sekiro easier and more fun/rewarding to play, than Dark Souls.  3) Hard core DS players who say Sekiro is a bad game becasue difficult in a wrong way are just wrong. It is \"not difficult but just different\", and that is the exact thing they were saying about Dark Souls. FULL REVIEW  (some minior spoilers) I confidently belive that Sekiro is objectively better than previous games, and I do love Dark Souls games with all my heart. It is a step forward in many aspects, and also a breath of fresh in some that were already exploited heavily, also by imitating developers of \"Souls-like genre\". I find it uncanny that From still wanted to evolve even when such a succesful formula could still provide them great income. You can read all about how Sekiro is \"different\" in many other reviews, so I will stop here. I also honeslty belive that it is better subiectively, for me, and probably for many other players, and I will try to explain that. The quick summary would be: there is a group of gamers with certain set of personal traits, who will find Sekiro easier and more fun/rewarding to play, than Dark Souls.  As much as I love Dark Souls games, for mostly everything that they stand for in artistic and game design ways, I pretty much sucked at each one of them. Don't get me wrong, I finished them all and got all achievements in DS1 and DS3, but it took me many hours, tears and screams. There are not many bosses that I've conquered in \"legit\" way. When I got tired by some boss walls I couldn't pass to go explore other parts of the magnificient world, I begun to use \"other means\", which included summoning NPC phantoms, co-op with my wife, summoning random players, farm levels for hours to make the boss easy by stats, and search internet for cheese methods and glitches. I rarely had a feel of victory everybody was talking about (the one of few exceptions I remember was the Abyss Watchers, whom I beat legit and alone after tens of tries, and yes... that felt amazing, even if my mouse needed surgery).  There could be many reasons, why I just couldn't git gut after so many hours, and some of them are things that comes from personal limitations, that are not easy, or near impossible to change only by practice. One is that I'm relatively old (37) for games like that and my response time is much slower, than when I was a kid and teenage gamer. This makes tactics \"wait for the particular boss move, react acordingly in the right millisecond, recognise how long the opening window will be, hit the exact amount of times\" very hard. This also made impossible for me to learn to parry, and I practised hours after watching instructional videos. I was always wrong, and rare parry was accidental, so I played mostly turtle build. I also have attention disorder, that made impossible for me to remember what I knew I suppose to do (which button to press) during stressful situations (which the boss fight actually is). And most irritable - that darn stamina bar. \"Remember stamina, remember stamina, remember stamina\" I repeated myself and always lost track over it and got killed when tried to perform and simply couldn't. Disorders like that also, in the heat of the fight, makes you forget that you prommised yourself not to be greedy this time and that result in many deaths near the end of boss healthbar. Becasue you just couldn't focus enough to be patient till the end. I could go on, but I think this is enough to paint the picture. Now, while those traits and limitations are not helpful in Sekiro, they are not such a terrible disatvantage. THERE IS NO STAMINA BAR IN SEKIRO. You don't have to split attention to check everytime you want to make a move. Also, the strategy of DS boss fighting is useless in here. I started to play Sekiro the way I tried to play Dark Souls and I sucked even more. First bosses was harder for me than any DS boss ever, and as usuall I started to search for a \"different ways\". No leveling exploit could save me this time. No summons either. And most funny, that when I tried to find cheese methods, they were actually hard to implement and finally resulted in me discovering how the game works! Because the game is stripped of some mechanics from Dark Souls, it is much better at THEACHING YOU THE ACTUAL SKILL, and that is most important step forward I could think of. Not only becasue usually you can find many videos of different \"cheese\" methods that are actually strategies which worked for someone, while something completely differet worked for others. Trying to defeat Genichiro Ashina with cheese methods helped me with first phase. Then I tried to cheese second phase by keeping all the spirit emblems, so I tried to defeat 1st normally, and that is when the game clicked for me. Finally I've beat the entire boss with no exploits, just learnig how to deflect. I've learned that this is totally different than DS, and then I actually BEGIN TO BE A BETTER SEKIRO PLAYER THEN I EVER WAS A DARK SOULS PLAYER AFTER HUNDREDS OF DARK HOURS. When fighting Guardian Ape I was much better with close combat, than using the run away method that most video guides suggest - BECAUSE THIS TACTIC IS STILL ROOTED IN DS PLAYSTYLE. Same thing I discovered with Phantom Corrupted Monk. No \"easy\" strategies by other gamers were helpful for me, but I've managed to win by combination of using some elements of all of them and just rhythmic deflecting. Isn't that a thing that defines a wonderfull game design? When there are so many ways of overcoming difficulties? Sekiro can be even played much better than DS by a typical button masher, bacause fighting is actually button mashing, but in specific rhythym. And that can become quickly an unconscious competence after few tries of first succesful deflect followed by the right rythym. You don't have to think about it, focus, wait for it and click in the right millisecond. Things get harder with special, unblockable moves, but it is managable to some degree even for someone like me. As a musician I can say that playing Sekiro resembles some elements of playing an instrument, where you also don't have to think. Both game styles have some elements in common but while Dark Souls relies more on a strategy and reflex, Sekiro will focus more on sense of rhythym and muscle memory. So as a summary, me, the Dark Souls CASUL is laughing at all the negative reviews by hard core DS players who say Sekiro is a bad game becasue difficult in a wrong way. It is \"not difficult but just different\", and that is the exact thing that you were saying to all crying, not gud players before Sekiro. Maybe this time this is the right game for me, and not the right game for you? Who knows, maybe there will be a game in the future, we both could enjoy as difficult in a fun way. [EDIT/P.S.] And for those people, who want to enjoy how this game is beautiful, it's landscapes, music, story, lore, level design, but are angry that there is no easy mode, in which they could skip that part of the game where you have to die a lot of times to learn and that is the only way you can feel victorious after finally conquering demanding boss fights (aaaand they are not interested in simply using cheats, which are also an option). THERE IS A COMMUNITY MADE, TOTALLY FREE EASY MODE AND YOU CAN FIND IT", "appid": "814380", "steamid": "profiles/76561198155547418", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "156", "votes_funny": "16", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1554724800.0}
