{"text": "2017â€™s   wasted no time in setting the gaming world alight, both with its unique approach of being an â€œindependent AAA game,â€ and for its treatment of mental health in the player-character, the titular Senua.  Itâ€™s a credit to developer Ninja Theory, that Senuaâ€™s psychosis is much more than a gimmick; itâ€™s a core gameplay mechanic, it drives the whole story, and it is a part of her. Sheâ€™s not a sexy badass warrior; sheâ€™s scared and overwhelmed, and the gameâ€™s stunning visual and sonic work constantly drives home how much of an uphill climb her journey is, which makes for an engrossing and compelling gaming experience. Combat is a welcome relief from the unrelenting mental assault, but also the gameâ€™s only weak spot. Too many times, I was backed into a corner, with the camera either becoming obscured, or so zoomed in as to be ineffective. It felt less like a metaphor for Senuaâ€™s psychosis, and more like a symptom of bad design. However, even in its simplicity (no distracting HUD or health bar), the combat is satisfying in its own right; after a barrage of auditory hallucinations challenging everything you do, hacking a monstrous VIking apparition into oblivion feels like an accomplishment.   is an intensely thought-provoking game that doesnâ€™t overstay its welcome; and on the rare occasions that it overplays its cards (either with the constant barrage of cues that scream THIS IS A GAME ABOUT MENTAL DISORDER, or the ending), itâ€™s well-deserved.", "appid": "414340", "steamid": "profiles/76561197980279310", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1594036800.0}
