{"text": "Years ago, the real-time strategy games consumed my time a lot, as I at least tried the vast majority of them.  , from 2003, was no exception, but it did not rank up among my favourites, so I was curious to see how I will enjoy this remastered version. Well, I got bored with the game during the first hours, but I still tried to find a way to like  . And while the second half of the campaign got my hopes up, it still was not enough for me to recommend this game. The game slightly follows   and his forcesâ€™ campaigns during the  , invasions of Britannia, skirmishes in Egypt and the Middle East, and  . That is a lot of conflicts, so it must sound interesting for the fans of this historical period. The problem is that there are barely any cutscenes or proper dialogues, and the ones present are so generic and uninteresting that you could put them into any conflict. I expected that there would be at least quotes from   memoirs or something. There is nothing, though. The game does not offer anything interesting for people who like this historical period or at least an intriguing story. The whole campaign feels like a mix of random missions without any proper connection rather than   road to triumph. What a shame. Well, who cares about the story if the gameplay is good, right? I wish I could say it in this case. Well, first and foremost,   primarily focus on combat. That is not necessarily a negative, as you would think that the game with such focus would have a good, enjoyable combat. The problem is that this is not really the case, and it just feels pretty tiresome to play   at times for the reasons I will describe below. As mentioned, the game has a campaign that is about twenty hours long. There is also a skirmish mode that revolves around destroying and defending villages. The problem is that most of the campaign missions feel like skirmish, as the objective is the same. Sometimes there is a fortress defense or escort mission, but most of the time, you will just conquer a village after village. It is just repetitive, boring, and forgettable. You start every mission with several units, which consists of multiple soldiers, and sometimes with a village too. Villages are preset locations in which your general recruits soldiers, and your only restriction is the current missionâ€™s unit limit. The one and only building you can build are defensive towers. That is all for some sort of management outside of combat. However, even with that little, the game manages to make it absolutely tedious. To capture a village, you have to, naturally, kill some enemies first. Once you do that, you have to destroy a garrison and kill an enemy commander. Then you have to rebuild it and put there your own commander. After that, you can begin with recruitment, and as the game presents itself as combat-focused, I would expect that it would be fast. You see, missions are usually long around half an hour. However, most of the unitâ€™s recruitment time is about one minute or even more. So, you can spend around five minutes or more waiting. And enemies did not even try to attack my defenseless villages most of the time! As you repeat this process in the campaign numerous times, it becomes monotonous, it just prolongs the gameplay, and it is not entertaining at all. As for the actual combat, there are three factions:  . They all have nine unit types, which are pretty similar to each other. There are light and heavy infantry, spearmen, archers, and melee and archer cavalry. Some units, like gladiators, can throw a net at enemy units, which stops them from moving. An interesting addition is that light infantry can build siege weapons, such as catapults, ladders, and battering rams. There are also special units, such as scouts or healers, which are pretty important for your army. As you would expect, the combat basically works on the â€œrock-paper-scissorsâ€ model. The problem is that it becomes boring after a while. There are no unitsâ€™ upgrades, no additional abilities except the basic ones. The content this game has is just not enough for what it tries to do. Also, Barbarians is one set faction, so their units are all the same in every part of Europe. The same applies to Egyptians, not only that their armour belongs to a completely different century, but Asian nations have Egyptian units too. Terrain plays a huge role in combat, as units can hide in forest and tall grass. Some units cannot go through woods and shallow water while others can. You can also destroy bridges or set the grass on fire. These additions are nice, as they occasionally make the combat more interesting. Now, the game still could be enjoyable if the enemy AI actually tried to fight me properly. That is not the case, though. Yes, AI has some simple scripts like: â€œSend cavalry on defenseless archers.â€. However, you can easily break AIâ€™s behaviour even with that example. I witnessed numerous times where AI just send cavalry on my spearmen. The campaign is boring that way because the AI will not train swordsmen to counter your spearmen. They will rather die the same way again and again. Unitsâ€™ pathfinding is also terrible, as you sometimes have to babysit their movement in mountains and such. Despite being remastered, the game is not that pretty, and there are not many details if you zoom closely to something. The developers did not even bother with redoing the CGI cutscenes, so they look absolutely terrible now. Sounds are nothing extraordinary either, and the person who reads the script sounds uninterested in his work. The soundtrack has a few themes that repeat constantly. To be honest, this should be free for the owners of the original rather than asking for money for it. The game was tested with an  , running at the highest settings, at  , at   resolution. The game crashed randomly six times throughout my playthrough.  might be a reasonable choice for someone new to the real-time strategy genre, as its mechanics are simple. However, I would still not recommend it to those people, as I would be rather afraid that they would lose interest in real-time strategy games pretty quickly.", "appid": "1100420", "steamid": "profiles/76561198111956371", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "25", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1602504000.0}
