{"text": "I didnâ€™t expect Lust from Beyond to receive a second prologue (hell, I donâ€™t think Iâ€™ve ever seen any developer promoting their final product this way), but here we are: itâ€™s hard for me to walk past free first-person horror-anything so it was only a matter of seconds to make up my mind, especially after the first prologue leaving a positive impression on me. Scarlet might have retained a large portion of pros and cons from the previous game, but it also introduces mechanics Iâ€™m not entirely sure the final version will improve upon, given how close we are nearing its release. More on that belowâ€¦ The player assumes the role of Alan, some nutjob with a rather concerning, ahem, â€œmasturbation-frequency-cycleâ€ . Now I donâ€™t know how he brought the news to his friend, but either way he assisted him in getting hooked up with a girl online, with their meeting point being a busted up and abandoned theater: it does raise suspicion in Alan after entering the building and observing his environment, but he decides heâ€™s already far too deep to quit and Iâ€™m definitely not referring to his date. The ominous setup should have been enough for anyone to nope out in 2 seconds flat, but not for Alan: after all, this is just making everything kinkier, itâ€™s all part of the show right? Coming across a piece of paper basically telling him â€œyou arenâ€™t the first idiot to fall for itâ€, itâ€™s already too late: Alan is being held in captivity by cultists forcing him to work through â€œtrialsâ€ allowing him to travel the slimy, disgusting halls of Lusstâ€™ghaa. Eventually, the portals to the World of Horny play into his advantage and he attempts to escape, only to end up in the seat of a therapist who is just as invested in the whole lust-themed matter. With that being said, Alan jumps from one frying pan into another and his fate seems to be sealed, but the ending screen implies otherwise.  Once again, itâ€™s a simple game of walking, exploring, reading and watching: the graphics are almost up to scratch, really love the emphasis on red colors / lights and I myself prefer an abandoned theater as the main location over the Victorian mansion. The sound design is not deserving of high praise, but gets the job done in setting the mood. I canâ€™t say I found the voice acting awful, the cultists may be overdoing it with the edginess but the phone conversations seem accurate, at least if itâ€™s someone with a chronic masturbation problem desperately trying to score. The most glaring and off-putting flaws are definitely in the short stealth and fighting segments: there is no point in hiding if you can outrun the AI so easily and if the game warns you of utilizing combat as the last resort, itâ€™s essentially another way of saying â€œour combat blows so please donâ€™t use it as muchâ€, because that is what it does. I didnâ€™t mind the lack of an FOV slider (again) until experiencing those visual effects of taken damage and lost sanity, the image zooms in so hard I could throw up. The movement still feels jittery, a complaint I voiced in the first 2 games as well: 60FPS donâ€™t feel like 60FPS, itâ€™s an atmosphere killer and none of the video settings can fix it. And donâ€™t even get me started on the plain obvious puzzle solutions, itâ€™s as if the developers think we shouldnâ€™t rely on using our brains a little and should instead maintain full focus on the shock values of sexual torture andâ€¦. scat? To each his own.  Scarlet is a clearly the more inferior segment out of the two, but the potential is undeniably there. Although the content Iâ€™ve seen here lessened my interest in purchasing Lust from Beyond on release (I rarely do that, anyway), Iâ€™m still curious as to what else the lore surrounding the world of Lusstâ€™ghaa has got in store for us.", "appid": "1401680", "steamid": "profiles/76561197991860447", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1602849600.0}
